00:00:00.459 --> 00:00:04.710
&gt;&gt;Cliff: So, good afternoon everyone. Welcome
to another awesome Authors@Google talk. Today,

00:00:04.710 --> 00:00:08.400
we're particularly honored to host Eboo Patel.

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:13.430
Now, as part of the Campus Honors Program
at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign,

00:00:13.430 --> 00:00:18.039
the name Eboo Patel is always displayed prominently
on our walls, it's sort of a myth and legend

00:00:18.039 --> 00:00:22.901
thing as, as we progress through the program;
someone larger than life. And that's, to a

00:00:22.901 --> 00:00:26.579
certain extent who Eboo is; he's always striving
for the greater good.

00:00:26.579 --> 00:00:30.869
He found his calling through the promotion
of interfaith dialogue, making the interfaith

00:00:30.869 --> 00:00:35.850
conversation as, as important and relevant
as the environmental con-, conversation, the

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:40.720
social justice conversation, and he's found
his particular outlet on, on college campuses,

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:47.519
which is a, a traditional area for, for discussion
and, and un-, understanding. And E-, Eboo's

00:00:47.519 --> 00:00:52.999
team has made a big impact in terms of fostering
interfaith dialogue on college campuses.

00:00:52.999 --> 00:00:57.379
Now, his work does reach beyond the college
campus and the University. He serves currently

00:00:57.379 --> 00:01:02.409
on the board of President Obama's Religious
Advisory Committee, and he writes regularly

00:01:02.409 --> 00:01:07.920
for The Washington Post in a, a blog that
deals with interfaith issues. It's entitled,

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.520
"The Faith Divide."

00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:13.420
Today, he'll be speaking to us about his work
through his non-profit, which is the Interfaith

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:18.280
Youth Corps, and as well as his book, his
book, which is entitled, "Acts of Faith: The

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:23.079
Story of an American Muslim, the Struggle
for the Soul of a Generation." Now, Eboo has

00:01:23.079 --> 00:01:28.009
many titles and awards from being a, a Rhodes
Scholar to an Ashoka Fellow to a, a member

00:01:28.009 --> 00:01:31.619
of the, the National Committee of the Aga
Khan Foundation.

00:01:31.619 --> 00:01:36.770
He's one of the social entrepreneurs to watch
on our nation's stage, but, but his true merit

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:41.649
lies in his impact in work and by fostering
interfaith dialogue, Eboo helps make the world

00:01:41.649 --> 00:01:45.980
truly a better place. So, we'll have some
time for Q&amp;A at the end. Feel free to use

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:49.090
the, the mics and otherwise, please join me
in welcoming Eboo to Google.

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:55.130
[applause]

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:56.130
Thank you.

00:01:56.130 --> 00:01:59.270
&gt;&gt;Patel: Thank you. Well, thank you to my
fellow Ilini, Cliff. Thank you, too, Usma,

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:05.620
Mahin, and Cliff, for hosting me for lunch.
Thank you to Google. This, you wanna talk

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:13.390
about legend, this company is legend, this
campus is legend, and I was joking with Usma

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:18.640
and Mahin, and Cliff earlier saying, "I've
long wanted to visit Google, but I felt a

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:23.390
little peculiar about being a tourist here."
So, when I got the, the invitation to come

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:27.410
speak I thought, "Well, you know, this is,
this is my opportunity to kind of get an oogle

00:02:27.410 --> 00:02:33.440
at Google, if you will, and see the famous
pool tables and the coffee shops and the cafeterias

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.370
and, and the tents and, thank you."

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:43.620
Thank you. Thank you for, for being part of
a generation that envisioned a new world and

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:47.570
then built that world. And that's what we're
trying to do in our own way at the Interfaith

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:54.460
Youth Corps. And I wanna, what I wanna describe
for you is, is where that vision came from,

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:59.640
what that vision is, and how we're trying
to build it. And then what I'd love is your

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:05.620
advice. I mean your advice as a community
of people who, as I said, have imagined a

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:13.840
new world and then built that new world, right?
How, how could you counsel us in dramatically

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.700
expanding our reach and our impact?

00:03:17.700 --> 00:03:22.790
So, to begin with, I wanna take you back to
a place that Cliff and I happen to share,

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:26.590
which is the University of Illinois, and I
understand that there's a pretty good pipeline

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:32.930
from Champaign Urbana, Illinois to Mountain
View, California, a set of very, very talented

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:38.330
computer engineers who are working here at
Google and I wanna tell you that, that my

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:45.890
year, my time in Champaign was a dramatic
paradigm shift for me. My, and, and the paradigm

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:52.900
shift was largely around issues of identity
and diversity, right? I grew up as a, as a

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:59.480
person of color, an Indian American who's
Muslim in the suburbs of Chicago and, you

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:05.100
know, frankly, I, I spent a lot of time trying
to be white in the western suburbs of Chicago

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:09.510
because that's was kind of the dominant cultural
archetype.

00:04:09.510 --> 00:04:14.500
And when I got to the University of Illinois,
I became part of a conversation about what

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:20.049
does it mean to build a truly multicultural
America where people are proud of their racial,

00:04:20.049 --> 00:04:25.330
their ethnic, their national backgrounds,
and where they're contributing the best of

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:30.009
those backgrounds to build this, this nation
that has gathered people from the four corners

00:04:30.009 --> 00:04:36.719
of the Earth. And the multicultural conversation
was very, very prominent in the mid 1990s

00:04:36.719 --> 00:04:40.211
all over the country and including the University
of Illinois.

00:04:40.211 --> 00:04:45.810
And like any good 17-year old, first year
student, I would go home to my parent's house

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:51.430
in Glen Ellyn and I would regale my father
with all my newfound wisdom from my first

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:56.051
year in college. And I would lecture him over
and over again about identity and diversity

00:04:56.051 --> 00:05:01.009
and my dad would kind of roll his eyes and
be like, you know, "I got my MBA from Notre

00:05:01.009 --> 00:05:06.371
Dame University in South Bend, Indiana, and
I was one of the first Indian Americans in

00:05:06.371 --> 00:05:10.729
a senior position in corporate advertising.
You think I don't know something about diversity?

00:05:10.729 --> 00:05:16.659
And you think I don't know something about
trying to advance multiculturalism?"

00:05:16.659 --> 00:05:21.729
My dad said one thing to me, which not only
struck me deeply at that point, but frankly,

00:05:21.729 --> 00:05:27.110
changed my life. And he said, "For all your
talk about identity and diversity, you, you

00:05:27.110 --> 00:05:33.749
never mentioned the form of identity and the
type of diversity that's driving global politics.

00:05:33.749 --> 00:05:41.949
And that's religion." My dad was exactly right.
Think about '93, '94, '95, '96, that mid to

00:05:41.949 --> 00:05:43.060
late 1990s.

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:48.699
Think about some of the most prominent global
events during that time. There was the World

00:05:48.699 --> 00:05:54.069
Trade Center bombing in 1993, kind of Al-Qaeda's
coming out party, if you will, there was the

00:05:54.069 --> 00:06:00.439
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin in the Middle
East, there was the possibilities represented

00:06:00.439 --> 00:06:05.340
by the Oslo Process and then the breakdown
of that process, there was a nuclear test

00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:11.139
in India dubbed, "The Hindu Bomb," there was
the response in Pakistan dubbed, "The Muslim

00:06:11.139 --> 00:06:19.659
Bomb," there was a, a terrible rampage through
Champaign, Illinois and Chicago and Bloomington,

00:06:19.659 --> 00:06:27.389
Indiana, somebody who shot and targeted Jews,
Asian Americans, and African Americans.

00:06:27.389 --> 00:06:35.039
And each of those incidents of horror, you
know, an additional one is the bombing at

00:06:35.039 --> 00:06:41.710
the Atlanta Olympics in 1996, each of those
incidents of horror was perpetrated to the

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:47.069
soundtrack of prayer. It was committed in
the name of God, right? And what's interesting

00:06:47.069 --> 00:06:53.159
is that the perpetrators came from different
religions, so Al-Qaeda clearly claims Muslim

00:06:53.159 --> 00:07:00.159
heritage. The assassin of Yitzhak Rabin in
1995 was Jewish; claims Jewish heritage.

00:07:00.159 --> 00:07:06.870
The person who shot Jews, African Americans,
and Asian Americans in, in the Midwest, was

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:13.999
part of the Christian Identity movement, right?
So, a huge part of national and global politics

00:07:13.999 --> 00:07:19.449
was this emergence of religious extremism.
And Sam Huntington, the late Harvard political

00:07:19.449 --> 00:07:25.309
scientist, put a framework on this. For my
money, a very dangerous framework. He said

00:07:25.309 --> 00:07:31.770
that the next era in human history was gonna
be defined by what he called "The Clash of

00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:32.770
Civilizations."

00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:38.289
The simple definition of the Clash of Civilizations
is that people from different religious backgrounds

00:07:38.289 --> 00:07:43.490
were inherently and inevitably at odds with
each other, right? We were gonna enter a period

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:48.460
of inter-religious war. So, his message to
people from different religions is espe-,

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:54.180
is essentially that people from the other
faith are coming; sharpen your swords, right?

00:07:54.180 --> 00:08:00.120
You have to if, if, if, if you don't wanna
die, you have to, you have to prepare to defeat

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:05.800
and kill and win, right? That's the message
of the Clash of Civilizations. And my dad

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:07.969
was exactly right.

00:08:07.969 --> 00:08:14.379
There was almost no discussion of this on
my college campus. And Diana Eck, a professor

00:08:14.379 --> 00:08:18.400
at Harvard, who writes on religious diversity,
actually pointed out that there was almost

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:22.840
no discussion of religion in the diversity
multicultural conversation nationally. She

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:29.699
says religion is the missing "R" in the diversity
conversation. And not only was this missing,

00:08:29.699 --> 00:08:34.380
in kind of a global macro way, it was also
missing in a personal way and there's something

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:40.070
that happened when I was a resident advisor
at the University of Illinois that I, I still

00:08:40.070 --> 00:08:41.950
remember.

00:08:41.950 --> 00:08:48.510
So, again, this is in the midst in the multicultural
movement where, where we are often invited

00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:53.610
to share our identities and to talk about
how we might have met-, been made to feel

00:08:53.610 --> 00:08:57.370
uncomfortable because of a certain part of
our identity. So, we're having this type of

00:08:57.370 --> 00:09:01.820
workshop as a group of resident advisors at
the University of Illinois and people are

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:06.810
saying, "Well, you know, as an African American,
you know, this happened to me. As a Latino

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:11.110
American, this happened to me that made me
feel uncomfortable or marginalized."

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:16.120
So, it gets around to my friend Kizar and
Kizar says, "You know, there was something

00:09:16.120 --> 00:09:20.950
that happened in the cafeteria a couple weeks
ago that made me feel really uncomfortable."

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:25.630
There was a group of student who basically
had a food fight, who kept on getting food

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:31.111
and throwing it around and, and everybody,
including the resident advisors and the cafeteria

00:09:31.111 --> 00:09:36.550
workers, they were all laughing and effectively
encouraging this terrible waste of food. And

00:09:36.550 --> 00:09:43.050
Kizar said, you know, "For me, food is life
and life is from God and that is precious

00:09:43.050 --> 00:09:49.010
because I'm a Muslim and, so I was a little
bit offended by what happened. As I looked

00:09:49.010 --> 00:09:53.180
around at the faces of these resident advisors
and these other kind of campus leaders of

00:09:53.180 --> 00:09:58.570
the University of Illinois, people who are,
you know, trained to be aware of how people's

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:03.350
identities affect their lives, blank stares."

00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:08.770
They weren't opposed to what Kizar was saying;
they just had no radar screen for it. They

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:15.180
had no radar screen for somebody making salient
their religious identity and the role it played

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:22.010
in their lives. And I thought to myself, "Wow.
You know, we're missing a great opportunity

00:10:22.010 --> 00:10:29.270
here, right? Because at the global, political
level, the story that's being written is a

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:34.930
story of religions and conflict with each
other. And who seemed to be the perpetrators

00:10:34.930 --> 00:10:39.680
of that conflict? Who, who were, were the
foot soldiers of religious extremism?

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:46.230
They're always teenagers and twenty-something's,
right?" I mean, the assassin of Yitzhak Rabin

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:52.930
is 26 years old. Almost all of the September
11th hijackers; in their twenties, right?

00:10:52.930 --> 00:11:01.740
Osama bin Laden recruited into extremism when
he's14 years old, right? The person who bombs

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:07.540
the Atlanta Olympics, part of the Christian
Identity movement, is just 30 years old. Religious

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:11.530
extremism is a movement of young people taking
action.

00:11:11.530 --> 00:11:17.490
Well, here was this other movement happening
on college campuses of young people who wanted

00:11:17.490 --> 00:11:23.340
to be aware, in an appreciative way, of identities
that mattered to people and to bring those

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:29.060
identities into harmony and cooperation, but
we weren't talking about religion. We were

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:34.310
forfeiting that territory to the religious
extremists of the world. I thought to myself,

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:40.260
"You know, we, we oughtta be able to do something
different. We oughtta be able to do something

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:41.260
different."

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:44.970
And, and one of the things that gave me an
awful lot of encouragement and inspiration

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:51.760
was history, you know? So much of the 20th
century's most inspiring movements are actually

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:57.140
interfaith movements started by young people.
So, Martin Luther King Jr. is obviously a

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:02.490
great civil rights hero, he's a great African
American hero, he's a great American figure,

00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:09.480
but he's also a great interfaith hero. Now,
King, after all was inspired by Gandhi's movement

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:16.190
in, in India. He marched in Selma with Rabbi
Abraham Joshua Heschel; he carried out a correspondence

00:12:16.190 --> 00:12:22.000
that deeply influenced him by a Buddhist monk
named The Venerable Thich Nhat Hahn, right?

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.630
King learns from people from a variety of
religious backgrounds even as he s-, remains

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:33.000
deeply, deeply rooted in his own Christian
faith and he learns how to bring people from

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.570
different religions together to serve the
common good. The Civil Rights movement is

00:12:37.570 --> 00:12:43.220
an interfaith movement. Same with Gandhi's
Hintz Barrage movement in India, same with

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:50.760
the struggle in South Africa, right? Same
with movements like community organizing;

00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:53.360
these are interfaith movements.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:58.620
And so, I think to myself, "If those were
movements that were built of the early and

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:04.610
mid-late part of the 20th centuries, couldn't
we be part of writing the next chapter in

00:13:04.610 --> 00:13:11.200
interfaith cooperation, especially in an era
of global religious conflict?" Final inspiring

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:18.610
dimension from history: the people who started
those interfaith movements, they're our age,

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:26.070
younger. King, in Montgomery in 1955, when
he led the bus boycott, was 26 years old.

00:13:26.070 --> 00:13:31.690
Mandela, when he founds the Youth League of
the African National Congress; 26 years old.

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:35.310
Gandhi, when he starts the movement against
the racist pass laws of South Africa in the

00:13:35.310 --> 00:13:43.400
early 20th century; 24 years old. The Dalai
Lama, when he moves Tibetans into India; 24

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:50.710
years old, right? Well, if interfaith cooperation
in previous eras was a movement of young people,

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:58.470
why not today? Why can't we make the story
of young people's involvement in religious

00:13:58.470 --> 00:14:02.840
diversity in the 21st century, not a story
of the Clash of Civilizations, but a story

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:05.540
of interfaith cooperation?

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:11.640
I think religion in the 21st century can go
one of four basic directions. It can be a

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:16.660
bubble of isolation, you can say that your
religious commitment or your, your humanist

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:20.860
commitment, whatever it might be, walls you
off from everybody different and if you're

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:25.250
a Muslim, you can't talk to anybody else.
If you're a Hindu or a Christian or a Humanist,

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:28.610
you can't have any dealings with anybody else
from a different background, so it can be

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:34.290
a bubble. It can be a barrier of division.
Your religion is so different from anybody

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:38.120
else's that you're actually in an oppositional
tension.

00:14:38.120 --> 00:14:43.670
It can be a bomb of destruction, you know,
you feel like you need to dominate people

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:50.310
from other backgrounds, violently. Or, it
can be a bridge of cooperation. The 21st century

00:14:50.310 --> 00:14:54.380
could lift up the best of the spirit of the
Civil Rights movement, the best of the spirit

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:58.550
of the south-, the, the struggle in South
Africa, the best of the spirit of the Settlement

00:14:58.550 --> 00:15:03.350
House Movement in the United States, and say
that people from different religious backgrounds,

00:15:03.350 --> 00:15:08.670
including no religion at all, ought to interact
in ways that build understanding and cooperation.

00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:14.520
We oughtta be building bridges, right? I think
that there are four main trends in the world

00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:19.380
that make this one of the great topics of
our times, right? Trend number one is we're

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:24.300
living during a time of religious revival.
You know, the best sociologists forty years

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:29.450
ago, people like Peter Berger, many, many
other were saying that, you know, religion

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:36.970
is dead. As societies modernize, they secularize
necessarily, right? Well, a lot of those sociologists,

00:15:36.970 --> 00:15:41.660
in light of you know, recent movements and
trends and demographics, say that they made

00:15:41.660 --> 00:15:47.600
what Berger calls a "category mistake." Modernity
doesn't so much secularize as it pluralizes,

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:53.680
right? And, indeed, what numbers show right
now is that there's, there's religion, as

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:59.150
Peter Berger says, "The world is as religious
as it ever was; perhaps more furiously religious

00:15:59.150 --> 00:16:03.750
than ever." Right? Sure, there's a growth
in people who call themselves nonbelievers,

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:10.750
but there's increased fervence in a particular
set of believers, especially in areas of the

00:16:10.750 --> 00:16:15.350
world defined by the second trend. The second
trend is the "youth bulge".

00:16:15.350 --> 00:16:20.200
We live in a very, very young world. You at
Google are probably hyperaware of this because

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:26.730
a lot of, so many people who are fast adopters
of new Google technologies and approaches

00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:30.880
are very young people because they're, they're
the first ones who kind of, you know, they

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:35.180
don't have to go from a landline to a cell
phone. They just go straight to a cell phone

00:16:35.180 --> 00:16:39.920
and then whatever the next technology is that
you guys are, are, are developing here. Lemme

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:47.440
give you some stats on this. The median age
in Iraq is 19.5. The median age in Afghanistan

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:54.560
is 17.6. There are more children in India
than there are citizens of the United States,

00:16:54.560 --> 00:17:00.720
and none of those places is the youngest place
on the planet. That award goes to Uganda,

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:07.870
right? How are all these young people gonna
view their identities in an era of religious

00:17:07.870 --> 00:17:15.019
revival? Are they gonna view them, those identities,
as bubbles, as bombs, as barriers, or as bridges?

00:17:15.019 --> 00:17:21.919
Ok, third trend that I wanna make salient
is the breakdown of traditional socioeconomic

00:17:21.919 --> 00:17:30.299
patterns. Very simply, for much of human history,
people have expected to live the type of life,

00:17:30.299 --> 00:17:35.259
have the kind of job, have the kind of family,
have the kind of socioeconomic pattern, if

00:17:35.259 --> 00:17:42.759
you will, that their parents had, right? Well,
those jobs don't exist anymore from, you know,

00:17:42.759 --> 00:17:50.600
Kansas City to Cairo to Cape Town, right?
And if the same jobs don't exist then you

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:53.929
can't build a family structure on top of those
jobs, right?

00:17:53.929 --> 00:18:01.289
You're, you're seeing entire socioeconomic
patterns, entire waves, ways of life disappear.

00:18:01.289 --> 00:18:07.830
And what that does is make identity questions.
"Who am I?" questions that much more acute,

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:13.139
that much sharper, right? Because you no longer
have the same kind of identity in being a,

00:18:13.139 --> 00:18:21.129
a worker at a GM factory or being a worker
at a government office in Cairo. So, you're

00:18:21.129 --> 00:18:26.039
constantly saying, "Who am I and what type
of pattern, what type of life pattern am I

00:18:26.039 --> 00:18:27.429
expected to live?"

00:18:27.429 --> 00:18:32.080
The fourth trend, another type of, another
thing you guys are hyperaware of here at Google,

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:37.110
and in fact, a trend that you have dramatically
accelerated, is the increase in interaction

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:45.509
by people from different backgrounds, ok?
So, just about everybody on Earth right now

00:18:45.509 --> 00:18:51.240
is aware that there are people who are very
different than them on Earth. And think about

00:18:51.240 --> 00:18:53.720
how shocking that is.

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:59.639
If you weren't aware, if, if, if you thought
that the whole world went to church on Sunday,

00:18:59.639 --> 00:19:05.320
right, you're entire town of seven hundred
people goes to church on Sunday and then one

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:10.809
person moves in to your town who doesn't go
to church, right? Or you're aware of somebody

00:19:10.809 --> 00:19:14.399
on the other side of the world because of
some Google application that puts you in touch

00:19:14.399 --> 00:19:20.520
with that person, of somebody who prays very
differently, or doesn't pray at all, doesn't

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:26.240
believe in God at all or believes in a, in
one God fervently, or believes that Jesus

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:30.230
is the son of God when you believe Jesus is
a prophet of God, right?

00:19:30.230 --> 00:19:37.539
You start asking yourself two, deep, gut level
questions. Question number one: If that person

00:19:37.539 --> 00:19:42.450
believes something differently, why do I believe
what I believe? If the Buddhist kid who just

00:19:42.450 --> 00:19:47.899
moved into my town doesn't go to church on
Sunday, why do I go to church on Sunday? Now

00:19:47.899 --> 00:19:54.340
what you took for granted because it was your
whole world before, because, you know, all

00:19:54.340 --> 00:20:01.799
you knew is a fish was water, right? When
somebody shows you air, you start to ask yourself

00:20:01.799 --> 00:20:04.669
the question, "Why do I live in water?"

00:20:04.669 --> 00:20:13.580
And the second question it makes salient is:
How do I relate to that person? So, she doesn't

00:20:13.580 --> 00:20:18.980
go to church on Sunday. He doesn't pray the
way that I do. She doesn't believe in God

00:20:18.980 --> 00:20:25.869
at all. So, what does that mean for how we
relate to each other? Right? So, think of

00:20:25.869 --> 00:20:31.610
the intersection of these four trends; the
religious revival, the youth bulge, the breakdown

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:37.320
of socioeconomic patterns, and the increase
in interaction of people from different backgrounds.

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:45.289
And, if you will, personify that for a moment.
Think of the 17 year old kid in Cairo, or

00:20:45.289 --> 00:20:51.980
the 17 year old kid in a favela outside of
