00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:31.220
a skill set. They have the ability to bring
people from different religious backgrounds

00:26:31.220 --> 00:26:37.210
together to build understanding and cooperation.
That's interfaith cooperation becoming a social

00:26:37.210 --> 00:26:38.210
norm.

00:26:38.210 --> 00:26:45.230
We think that there, that, that we can advance
three core strategies against this. Obviously,

00:26:45.230 --> 00:26:50.489
in any movement that becomes a social norm,
there are a thousand organizations. There

00:26:50.489 --> 00:26:55.529
are a million different niches. Environmentalism
has, you know, people who chain themselves

00:26:55.529 --> 00:27:00.730
to redwood trees and people who buy hybrid
cars and people who start recycling programs

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:04.080
in elementary schools and people who give
money to the Sierra Club, right?

00:27:04.080 --> 00:27:09.269
There are a million riffs on environmentalism,
but everybody knows that at the end of the

00:27:09.269 --> 00:27:14.659
day, what they're about is that the Earth
is precious it ought to be protected, right?

00:27:14.659 --> 00:27:19.039
For interfaith cooperation to become a social
norm, it has to be a field and a movement

00:27:19.039 --> 00:27:24.179
that's as diverse and large and robust as,
as any other movement; as environmentalism

00:27:24.179 --> 00:27:29.370
or human rights or civil rights or service
learning. We would like to advance three key

00:27:29.370 --> 00:27:30.700
strategies.

00:27:30.700 --> 00:27:37.789
Key strategy number one: We need to spread
a message and shape a discourse around interfaith

00:27:37.789 --> 00:27:45.789
cooperation. Part of what I woke up and realized
a couple years ago is every night, Al-Qaeda

00:27:45.789 --> 00:27:52.739
advertises "religion is violent" on the evening
news for free, right? If you want a commer-,

00:27:52.739 --> 00:27:56.880
if you're a toothpaste company, or a cola
company, or a car company and you wanna get

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:04.759
your message out on MSNBC or CNN or NBC, you
gotta pay $50,000 for 30 seconds or $200,000

00:28:04.759 --> 00:28:09.809
for 30 seconds, but if you're a religious
extremist group, all you have to do is videotape

00:28:09.809 --> 00:28:14.139
your beheading and send the videotape to a
media company. And the media company plays

00:28:14.139 --> 00:28:15.139
it for free.

00:28:15.139 --> 00:28:20.019
Now what that effectively is, is an advertisement
for "religion is violent." So, what that means

00:28:20.019 --> 00:28:24.739
is there's a lot of people who walk around
the world and all they know about religion

00:28:24.739 --> 00:28:30.970
period, or somebody else's religion, is that
videotape, and I think that that's terrible,

00:28:30.970 --> 00:28:36.330
right? What does it look like for those of
us who believe in interfaith cooperation and

00:28:36.330 --> 00:28:41.940
who believe that religion can be a bridge
of positive cooperation, to be as aggressive,

00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:47.960
as strategic about advancing our message of
interfaith cooperation, of religion as a bridge,

00:28:47.960 --> 00:28:57.320
through media and policy circles? What does
it mean for us to, to shape a discourse that,

00:28:57.320 --> 00:29:04.619
that says that religions, although they have
clear doctrinal differences, also have very

00:29:04.619 --> 00:29:09.789
important shared values? Show me a religion
that doesn't value mercy. Show me a religion

00:29:09.789 --> 00:29:15.770
that doesn't value compassion, hospitality,
service, right? The message that we have to

00:29:15.770 --> 00:29:21.360
send is that religious communities can come
together on these shared values.

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:26.249
Those values are mutually enriching and they
are actionable and that ought to be part of

00:29:26.249 --> 00:29:33.129
the character of the next era. We cannot forfeit
the, the space of the media or the policy

00:29:33.129 --> 00:29:39.129
to people who believe in the Clash of Civilizations.
We have to make sure that that space is imbued

00:29:39.129 --> 00:29:44.679
with the message of interfaith cooperation.
Strategy number two: We believe a sector needs

00:29:44.679 --> 00:29:49.549
to show what "good" looks like, you know?
One of the things that I love about Google

00:29:49.549 --> 00:29:54.559
is that, in so many ways, this is a company
that shows what "good" looks like; how it

00:29:54.559 --> 00:29:56.989
should treat its employees, right?

00:29:56.989 --> 00:30:02.129
And so many other companies have had to follow
the lead of Google to the benefit of the workforce

00:30:02.129 --> 00:30:07.639
around the country and the world. We think
that college campuses can show what "good"

00:30:07.639 --> 00:30:11.879
looks like when it comes to interfaith cooperation.
Just like college campuses that are around

00:30:11.879 --> 00:30:18.149
multiculturalism and sensitize people to the
importance of, of ethnic and racial and national

00:30:18.149 --> 00:30:23.159
identity, and sought to build a culture where
people from different racial and ethnic and

00:30:23.159 --> 00:30:27.470
national backgrounds were coming together
in a spirit of cooperation.

00:30:27.470 --> 00:30:31.379
College campuses are places where there are
different religious student groups; where

00:30:31.379 --> 00:30:36.029
there's a volunteer office, where there's
an ethos of leadership development, where

00:30:36.029 --> 00:30:41.549
there is a, a sense of being on the vanguard.
Why shouldn't every college campus consider

00:30:41.549 --> 00:30:47.470
it part of its mission to model interfaith
cooperation? Every college campus has days

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:52.370
of interfaith service. College presidents
give inaugural speeches to the freshman class

00:30:52.370 --> 00:30:57.210
about the importance of religious diversity
and engaging it positively. Well, there are

00:30:57.210 --> 00:31:03.220
academic courses that builds peoples knowledge
base and skill set in interfaith cooperation.

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:08.529
Orientation leaders, our age, are trained
in religious diversity and interfaith cooperation,

00:31:08.529 --> 00:31:13.139
right? College campuses can show what "good"
looks like.

00:31:13.139 --> 00:31:18.100
And that has, there are two clear benefits
to that. One, is it's a sector that other

00:31:18.100 --> 00:31:23.409
people follow, ok? I'm pretty convinced that
if college campuses show what "good" looks

00:31:23.409 --> 00:31:30.889
like, the corporate sector will follow, high
schools will follow, municipalities will follow,

00:31:30.889 --> 00:31:34.590
right? Higher education likes to serve as
the vanguard. I think they ought to serve

00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:36.469
as a vanguard in this area.

00:31:36.469 --> 00:31:43.269
The second thing is that higher education
trains a nations next generation of leaders.

00:31:43.269 --> 00:31:49.080
So, if you have a generation of leaders who
are imbued with the importance of interfaith

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:53.730
